<TextBlock Name="Text001_None" IsManipulationEnabled="False" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,0,0,20" Width="450" Height="200" FontFamily="MV Boli" FontSize="41" Foreground="#FF8B0000">Coordinate Systems:  Cartesian versus Polar<TextBlock.RenderTransform><MatrixTransform><MatrixTransform.Matrix><Matrix OffsetX ="300" OffsetY="17" M11="1" M22="1" /></MatrixTransform.Matrix></MatrixTransform></TextBlock.RenderTransform></TextBlock>
<TextBlock Name="Text002_None" IsManipulationEnabled="False" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,0,0,20" Width="999" Height="96" FontFamily="MV Boli" FontSize="18" Foreground="#FF8B0000">How do you describe where something is?  Well, you might say that an object is to the left or far away.  What you just used to describe the object's place is more or less a coordinate system.  Let's take a look at two very common coordinate systems used in mathematics.<TextBlock.RenderTransform><MatrixTransform><MatrixTransform.Matrix><Matrix OffsetX ="23" OffsetY="148" M11="1" M22="1" /></MatrixTransform.Matrix></MatrixTransform></TextBlock.RenderTransform></TextBlock>
<TextBlock Name="Text003_None" IsManipulationEnabled="False" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,0,0,20" Width="503" Height="111" FontFamily="MV Boli" FontSize="16" Foreground="#FF8B0000">Cartesian:  Don't let the name fool you.  The Cartesian coordinate system is the grid you've already become accustomed to in previous math classes.  It was originally developed for simplifying map coordinates and is still used in maps today.<TextBlock.RenderTransform><MatrixTransform><MatrixTransform.Matrix><Matrix OffsetX ="23" OffsetY="245" M11="1" M22="1" /></MatrixTransform.Matrix></MatrixTransform></TextBlock.RenderTransform></TextBlock>
<TextBlock Name="Text004_None" IsManipulationEnabled="False" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,0,0,20" Width="968" Height="75" FontFamily="MV Boli" FontSize="16" Foreground="#FF8B0000">The basic principle behind Cartesian is this:  Coordinates are described through two numbers, x and y in relation to two perpendicular lines or axes.  x describes the distance along the x-axis or to the left or right of the y-axis and y describes the distance along the y-axis or above or below the x-axis.  The form of coordinate is (x,y).<TextBlock.RenderTransform><MatrixTransform><MatrixTransform.Matrix><Matrix OffsetX ="23" OffsetY="353" M11="1" M22="1" /></MatrixTransform.Matrix></MatrixTransform></TextBlock.RenderTransform></TextBlock>
<TextBlock Name="Text005_None" IsManipulationEnabled="False" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,0,0,20" Width="489" Height="104" FontFamily="MV Boli" FontSize="16" Foreground="#FF8B0000">Polar:  The Polar coordinate system works similarly to how you use a compass.  Since a compass always points north, a point is described as a rotation from north and the distance from your spot directly to the point.<TextBlock.RenderTransform><MatrixTransform><MatrixTransform.Matrix><Matrix OffsetX ="20" OffsetY="446" M11="1" M22="1" /></MatrixTransform.Matrix></MatrixTransform></TextBlock.RenderTransform></TextBlock>
<TextBlock Name="Text006_None" IsManipulationEnabled="False" TextWrapping="Wrap" Margin="0,0,0,20" Width="1018" Height="103" FontFamily="MV Boli" FontSize="16" Foreground="#FF8B0000">Polar is almost identical to a compass, except the needle always points east, or the positive x-axis.  Coordinates are given r and the greek letter theta.  Theta symbolizes the rotation from east.  Positive theta means rotate counterclockwise and negative theta means rotate clockwise.  Theta is given in either degrees or radians  r is the distance from the origin directly to the point.  The form of the coordinate is (r,theta).<TextBlock.RenderTransform><MatrixTransform><MatrixTransform.Matrix><Matrix OffsetX ="19" OffsetY="555" M11="1" M22="1" /></MatrixTransform.Matrix></MatrixTransform></TextBlock.RenderTransform></TextBlock>
